00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:07.160
So let's, actually, I've got a thing that I'm working on at work that involves a project

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:10.300
that really should be set up as a monorepo.

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:15.740
So, I mean, it's not, we're really, we don't really do monorepo things.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:23.980
But I guess it's a project that has one repository and a bunch of different, like, Python projects

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:24.640
inside of it.

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:28.340
So I was looking for help with that.

00:02:28.700 --> 00:02:35.120
And I ran across this article called Three Things I Wish I Knew Before Setting Up a uv Workspace.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:41.540
And it is really about setting up a uv workspace to deal with monorepos.

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:44.500
And I actually don't really know.

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:45.460
Anyway.

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:49.660
So workspaces are a thing that uv can deal with.

00:02:49.660 --> 00:02:53.240
But there's some tricks that, I guess, weren't obvious.

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:54.300
They weren't obvious to me.

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:56.320
So there's just a few that I want to cover.

00:02:57.260 --> 00:03:00.820
One is to give the root a distinct name.

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:03.520
So you've got a top-level Py.

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:05.000
You've got an application.

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:06.400
You've got your repo.

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:11.940
There's going to be a top-level PyProject.toml to handle all of that, to cover everything.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:18.040
And then each of your sub-packages will have its own PyProject.toml.

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:26.580
And the trick is they've got to have the workspace names have to be different to make this all work.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.440
And so it might be obvious.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:34.380
It might, like, in the example, they've got MyApp as the core project.

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:36.400
But then the workspace is MyApp also.

00:03:36.580 --> 00:03:37.360
It can't be that.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.300
You run into a name conflict.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:47.260
So and that's in the names show up in a thing you've got member.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:55.140
There's an example of what the workspace looks like and that you have to set up a different top-level name.

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:58.080
So project name has to be different.

00:03:58.380 --> 00:04:01.760
So maybe obvious, but I would not.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:03.180
It wasn't obvious to me.

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:05.240
So thanks for that help.

00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:17.000
The other part, which one of the other tricky bits is in order for uv to deal with this okay, the top-level one – is it the top one?

00:04:18.020 --> 00:04:24.260
If workspace packages depend on each other, you've got to do a couple things.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:32.520
You have a normal dependency declaration and a tool.uv.sources entry telling uv to resolve it locally.

00:04:33.180 --> 00:04:34.940
So a project will have a dependency.

00:04:35.480 --> 00:04:36.680
It's going to have its own name.

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:37.900
It's going to have a dependency.

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:46.280
And that dependency, if it's internal, you have to, below, say, you know, look – also look for uv sources in this workspace.

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:50.760
So it doesn't go out to PyPI or whatever to try to find those dependencies.

00:04:50.760 --> 00:04:55.980
And, yeah, I would not have even thought that that's built into uv, so that's cool.

00:04:56.920 --> 00:04:58.100
Didn't know that was there.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:09.260
The third bit that was to use import lib mode for pytest, and that's kind of one of the reasons why I wanted to pick this,

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:12.020
because I'm not sure what they're talking about here.

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:22.220
Apparently, there's an issue – the issue is if you've got, like, something like the same test name, like test helpers in multiple projects.

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:26.680
If you have unique file names, it's fine.

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:33.640
But if you might not, and, you know, as projects grow, you don't want to, like, restrict people's file name choice,

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:36.440
we'll go ahead and do this.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:40.340
But I don't – there's, like, a couple methods.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:48.060
There's the use – the import lib method, and then there's putting dunder and nets in your test directory.

00:05:48.360 --> 00:05:52.880
And the comment here is that this is – there's a silent bug with that.

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:54.440
I wasn't familiar with this.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:06:04.680
So it's a homework for me for next week is to research this to try to figure out what the deal is with this import lib versus dunder and net and how that behaves.

