00:07:43.840 --> 00:07:48.400
So C adders is actually, it works with adders and data classes.

00:07:49.080 --> 00:07:59.540
And its job is to take and do very similar serialization and validation that you would find in Pydantic, but have it as a separate library.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:25.540
And so one of the things that I'm realizing as I sort of go through these examples and when I chose my raw queries plus data classes pattern that we talked about last week, I think it was last week, recently, that I really was valuing the fact that the data classes themselves were just that, data classes.

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:32.540
And maybe they got their own computed properties or something, but they were not in charge of serialization, deserialization, validation.

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:50.200
But things like data class wizards and C adders, or just your data access layer, all those can have really rich conversions, parsing, validation, et cetera, without actually being part of your object hierarchy and your class.

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:52.200
So you can choose those things separately.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:53.480
And this is right along those lines.

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:55.040
So it's super cool.

00:08:56.100 --> 00:09:06.560
I can import structure and unstructure, which is to and from different types, but maybe dictionaries is the best mental model.

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:16.440
And so I can say just parse one of these things as a class C, which you defined as a data class or an adders class or something like that.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:20.100
And what you get out is one of those parsed and validated, right?

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:22.960
Or you can unstructure it and it becomes a dictionary.

00:09:23.640 --> 00:09:25.660
Okay, so that's pretty neat.

00:09:26.700 --> 00:09:31.680
But it's not just adders.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:35.180
It also works on data classes and let's see.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:40.520
There's a bunch of different types of validation.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.800
Let me see if I can find it here in our example.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.560
So it does things like a message spec, message pack.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:00.320
It does YAML, JSON, obviously.

00:10:00.320 --> 00:10:07.320
So there's a bunch of these different serialization libraries that you might adopt, right?

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:11.260
So it's really cool that you can do all different types of serialization and so on.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:13.600
And I think it's really cool.

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:22.080
You can set up hooks to help transform values and validate values through just basically decorators, which is kind of cool.

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:33.800
Yeah, so more or less, do you want a really nice structured way to serialize classes without making it part of the object hierarchy?

00:10:34.140 --> 00:10:34.840
Check out see adders.

00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:35.360
It's really cool.

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:36.340
Yeah.

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:47.340
Yeah, I really like see adders, especially for projects like not, I mean, reaching for a bid-and-addic seems like a natural thing to do with web stuff.

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:57.480
