00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:02.340
But yeah.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:03.220
Neat.

00:11:03.360 --> 00:11:03.500
Yeah.

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:05.560
I think it's really cool to have that control.

00:11:05.740 --> 00:11:13.860
Like, for example, what I talked about was if you use Pydantic, it's awesome that it serializes data before it gets into your database.

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:17.680
But it re-validates that data when it comes out of your database.

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:20.840
Why are you validating data that's just stored in your database?

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:21.780
You don't need to do that.

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:23.840
It just happens to be, well, that's how Pydantic works.

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:24.600
You load it with data.

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:25.300
It validates it.

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:25.640
Great.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:25.680
Right.

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:27.100
Right.

00:11:27.180 --> 00:11:35.660
So that's what I think is neat about this separation, this sort of orthogonality of your validation and conversion layer and your class structure.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:39.700
Because you can validate on the way in but not on the way out if that's how you like it.

00:11:39.740 --> 00:11:40.140
